iscuss camps and camping. There are different types and levels of camping. There's<br>  1. Dungeon room camping - Picking a spot that has several mobs or controls access to one or more areas containing desired mobs. Usually there is some risk or unavoidable mobs to get past, either via fighting or some form of invisibility. In some cases, a camp is not considered valid unless it is basically in the location with the mobs; this is usually the case when an area is overcrowded with people. <br><br>  Mobs that do not fit easily into one camp area or another may be contested, or an agreed upon compromise reached. (The old stairs pops in Highpass Keep were split between warrior room and raider room; Velk's has a first come first served mentality for most but not all spiders.)<br><br>  Generally, people split off sections of the dungeon into different camps and do not pull from outside their section unless other sections are not occupied by people. They usually accept, graciously or not, that other groups may move into those sections and claim those associated mobs.<br><br>  2. Outdoor camping - These can be broken into static single spawns, random roaming spawns, and static camps of multiple critters. <br><br>  Static camps mostly follow the dungeon camp rules, but with less respect. There is usually no difficulty in getting to those camps, and usually the mobs are of a lesser importance, especially for loot rewards. Several groups may contest over a camp, and wind up sharing (as seen in the dervish camp in WC). Taking a mob or two from one of these camps is still considered tacky at best, but usually a minor offense.<br><br>  Random roaming spawns are sometimes a point of serious contention, with ridiculous cries of camping and kill stealing. The South Ro Cyclops falls into this role, as do an infinite number of orc pawns. The more important or rare the loot on the mob, the more KSing involved. Camp calls have very little respect on these mobs.<br><br>  Static single spawns, usually for quests, include fun mobs like Stormfeather, Lodizal, and Ragefire. Usually no placeholders are required to be killed, leaving these mobs a simple waiting effort. There are varying degrees of camp mentality accepted, with no clear single acceptable answer for all parties. <br><br>  Most people accept that Stormfeather is camped by a high level melee player, because the quest reward is pretty useless for anyone else, and can't be chain quested. Lodizal, however, is considered first come, first served, IF you have sufficent forces present to kill him. Engaging first is not generally accepted by the players if all you can do is kite him around.<br><br>  Ragefire used to be a mostly accepted camp, on EMarr at least, because you had to clear the fire giants every 8 hours. There was an effort involved in being there, and maintaining the area, and the cleric involved was supposed to be there throughout. The change placing &quot;half&quot; of him in Skyfire has inherited the camp status of the old method, but the increased wait time and lack of mobs to clear has removed the respect for the camp status. There is a considerable effort to find a compromise system until Verant rethinks the quest yet again. <br><br><br>  Finally, there is kill stealing and camp stealing. Taking a mob no one has engaged or seems likely to engage in the next few minutes (time scaling up with the difficulty of the mob) is not kill stealing. Killing a mob someone else is legitimately and actively trying to kill is KSing. Killing a mob someone is prepping for can be considered KSing, depending on the importance of the mob and the condition that each party knows of the other party's intentions re: said mob. This is only a player endorsed definition.<br><br>  Camp stealing involves moving into someone else's area and killing mobs they consider theirs. In some cases, this involves taking a lesser camp area that the first group had added to their own. In other cases, it means the second group has moved to contest over the exact same mobs in the same area as the first group, usually resulting in petitioning or attempts to share too few mobs. Other types include dashing ahead of people clearing their way to a camp to setup, a very rude but not uncommon practice in crowded dungeons. <br><br>  The first condition usually results in grumbling over a group moving into an already &quot;broken&quot; spawn, but is otherwise accepted. The second and third types cause all manner of Hades to break out.<br><br><br><br>  There. Now if that didn't bore you to tears, go ahead and topic steal this thread. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukragarn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kragarn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 243<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/19/02 12:30:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3184.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Camps and KSing and more</span><hr size=1> Mitch should leave our board.  Mitch smells like ka-ka and no one likes him!<br><br>That oughta start the hijacking.<br> <p>Kragarn <br>Blackguard <br>Ring Warden of EMarr <br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ucthenobsidius.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cthen Obsidius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 352<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/19/02 6:22:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3184.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Camps and KSing and more</span><hr size=1> I think the smell is more of a distinct poo rather th